03985nam a22005055i 9780773562837DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735628377 a10.1515/97807735628372doi  a(DE-B1597)654675  a(OCoLC)732600956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1054.5.A38bR39 1991eb 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a971.3/751 aRayside, David M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSmall Town in Modern Times :bAlexandria, Ontario /cDavid M. Rayside. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4cÂ©1991  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Maps -- tPreface -- tThe Lie of the Land -- tIndustrial Development and Economic Dependence -- tThe World of Wage Labour -- tGender Identity and Inequality -- tLanguage and Schooling -- tCommunity Politics -- tFragmentation and Community -- tNotes -- tGuide to Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRayside conducted informal interviews with more than 150 Glengarrians and attended numerous meetings of local councils, school boards, planning boards, and conservation authorities. This field research provides the basis for a detailed examination of the self-image of the town as a friendly, caring, united community, and of the unequal power relations that exist between different social classes, language groups, and men and women. Working-class life is disadvantaged in Alexandria much as it is in large cities, French-English relations are strained, and the experience of women has not been affected to any great extent by the challenges of feminism. Local government in Alexandria may be more accessible to the ordinary citizen than it is elsewhere but, as Rayside shows, the local council rarely engages in issues of genuine concern to residents, who themselves largely ignore municipal politics. Most local politicians seem inclined to avoid controversy and innovation, hoping to retain an environment favourable to business investment. Rayside examines the impact of the external world on a small community. He situates this impact and the resulting changes in historical context and reveals economic and social relationships that differ from what many of Alexandria's inhabitants believe to be the case. A Small Town in Modern Times will be of interest not only to students and scholars of political science, sociology, history, and Canadian studies but also to residents of Alexandria and any other small community in transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356283740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562837423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562837/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles